## Textbook View — Polarity / Logic Invariants (Θ-System)

### 1.1 Core Invariants (Dual-Column)

| IGSOA / Θ-Language | Standard Logic / Intuition |
| :---- | :---- |
| Polarity Conservation Invariant (Θ\_INV\_CONSERVATION) Any valid Θ-evolution must conserve net polarity: the signed sum of Θ₊ and Θ₋ channels cannot change unless an explicit, declared source/sink operator is present. | Signed charge conservation. You can’t create or destroy “+ / − logical charge” by accident. All logic gates must account for input signs when producing outputs. |
| Polarity Tensor-Sign Invariant (Θ\_INV\_TENSOR\_SIGN) Any Θ-tensor contraction (ΣΘ, Θ⊗, Θ⊕) must preserve the global sign pattern of the tensor, up to explicitly declared sign-flip operators. | Safe tensor wiring. When you contract or sum polarised tensors, you cannot silently flip or erase sign information; you either keep it or flip it via an explicit “NOT/polarity” operator. |
| Truth-Polarity Bridge Invariant (Θ\_INV\_TRUTH\_BRIDGE) The Π-evaluation of a Θ-state must be compatible with its polarity: Θ₊ channels may not evaluate to Π \= ⊥ in ways that violate the declared truth-polarity mapping, and Θ₋ channels may not evaluate to Π \= ⊤ without an explicit contradiction/negation witness. | Truth ↔ sign consistency. If “+” means “true-aligned” and “−” means “false-aligned/negated,” then your truth tables must respect that. No gate is allowed to output “true” with a “negative” sign unless a proper NOT/contradiction step is present. |

### 1.2 What else goes in this Tier (for the textbook)

You can treat this Tier as the bridge between raw Θ-polarity and full semantic logic. Suggested subsections:

1. Signed Truth Tables  
   * Show ordinary AND/OR/NOT truth tables, then refine them with Θ₊ / Θ₋ annotations.  
   * Example: (a \= Θ₊, b \= Θ₋) into an AND gate and how the invariants constrain the output sign.  
2. Polarity Flow Diagrams  
   * Small diagrams where wires carry (Π, Θ) pairs.  
   * Mark invariant violations (e.g. a wire that “drops” polarity) in red and show how the rewrite system repairs them.  
3. Invariant-Safe Normal Form (ΘNF)  
   * Define ΘNF as: “A logic network is in ΘNF if all three invariants hold on every wire and gate.”  
   * Show a short network that violates Θ\_INV\_TRUTH\_BRIDGE and how a Θ-aware rewrite inserts an explicit NOT/contradiction node to restore ΘNF.  
4. Worked Example (matches JSON below)  
   * Two inputs a, b with (Π, Θ) pairs go through AND.  
   * Initial buggy design drops polarity on the output.  
   * Invariant checker flags violation of Θ\_INV\_CONSERVATION and Θ\_INV\_TENSOR\_SIGN.  
   * Rewrite system adds a Θ-router and sign aggregation so that output sign is derived as Θ(out) \= Θ(a) ⊕ Θ(b) and ΘNF is restored.
